feed.title: Macedon Range - Native Plants
feed.subtitle: This is a general collection for the whole Macedon Range including the Macedon Regional Park, Barrm Birrm (Riddells Creek), Barringo, Mt. Robertson, Mt Charlie, Mt Teneriffe, T-Hill and Conglomerate Gully.

entry.title: Persoonia chamaepeuce
entry.content: About 4 plants in this fenced biosite area between Middle Gully Road and the railway line south of Woodend. This is the third location for the Dwarf Geebung in the Macedon Ranges. Previously recorded in a gully at Barrm Birrm, Riddells Creek and along the rail line just south of the Macedon station. Not common in Macedon Ranges but may exist in other areas along the railway.

entry.title: Cassinia aculeata
entry.content: Species information: Erect shrub to about 3 m high. Leaves spreading, linear, 10â50 mm long, 1â2.5 mm wide, cottony beneath. Flowers heads, white, in large clusters. Flowers Nov - Feb

entry.title: Astroloma humifusum
entry.content: Species information: Usually a mat-forming low shrub to 50 cm high. Leaves 5â18 mm long, 0.6â3 mm wide, sharply pointed a tip, lower surface usually paler; margins toothed. Flowers bright red, tubular, often hidden by the foliage. Small sweet-tasting green-black berries. Flowers Jan - July

entry.title: Caladenia transitoria
entry.content: A patch of a dozen or more plants, each about 12 cm tall. First record for Macedon Ranges. It is small and easily overlooked. All had a single flower except two plants which had two flowers per stem.

entry.title: Thelymitra peniculata
entry.content: Leaves fleshy, distinctly ribbed on the outside. Apex of mid-lobe of column (yellow part) somewhat dorsally compressed with a V-notch. Lateral lobes of column with a terminal tuft of white hairs, extending horizontally and converging. More than 5 flowers per stem (I can count 7 or 8 including the buds).

entry.title: Caladenia moschata
entry.content: In my experience, Caladenia moschata can have a quite strongly vertically compressed dorsal sepal similar to C. cucullata but the second half of the labellum is not completely purple as in C. cucullata. I find that the detection of a strong musky scent is not a reliable feature.

entry.title: Cryptandra amara s.s.
entry.content: Close up of flowers, showing hood-like outgrowths of petals which closely cover the stamens. (Cryptandra = "hidden stamens"). Branchlets covered with fine stellate hairs. Leaves shortly petiolate, ovate to obovate or oblong, 2â5 mm long, 1â2 mm wide, mainly glabrous.

entry.title: Acrotriche serrulata
entry.content: Species information: Dense, prostrate to decumbent shrub to c. 30(â60) cm high; branchlets finely pubescent. Leaves linear-lanceolate to lanceolate, 3.5â11 mm long, 0.5â1.7 mm wide, with pointed tip (muronate). Flowers, green-translucent, small, on old wood near the ground. Flowers Jun - Nov

entry.title: Acrotriche prostrata
entry.content: Species information: Trailing shrub with main stems prostrate and rooting at intervals, branches prostrate or ascending to about 15 cm high. Leaves spreading, often more or less horizontal, lanceolate to ovate, 4â16 mm long, 1â8 mm wide, mucronate. Flowers not obvious in dense c. 5â14-flowered spikes, on previous season's or older wood. Flowers Apr - Jul

entry.title: Acacia stricta
entry.content: Species information: Shrub or tree, 1â5 m high, often suckering; branchlets angled towards extremities, striate with yellowish resin ribs, glabrous. Phyllodes ascending to erect, normally linear to linear-oblanceolate, 3.5â14 cm long, 3â10(â15)mm wide, straight to shallowly curved, thin, glabrous, dull, green to grey-green or subglaucous, obtuse; midrib prominent. Flower heads globular, 2-4 per leaf axil, cream to lemon-yellow, sometimes light golden, young buds mealy. Flowers mostly May - Oct

entry.title: Acacia leprosa var. graveolens
entry.content: syn. Acacia verniciflua (southern variant) Open shrub 2 - 5 m high. Phyllodes (30â)50â110 mm long and (3â)7â20(â30) mm wide, puncticulate; with 2 longitudinal nerves on each face. Gland usually at distal end of pulvinus, (1â)2â4 mm above the pulvinus Flowers Aug - Nov

entry.title: Acacia verticillata subsp. verticillata
entry.content: Species information: Spreading shrub or erect tree, 2 - 5 m tall. Phyllodes whorled, needle-like, 0.5â2.5 cm long, 0.5 -1.5 mm wide. Flowers pale yellow to yellow, in cylindrical spikes, to 2 cm long, 1 - 3 spikes per leaf axil. Flowers usually Jul.âDec.

entry.title: Acacia melanoxylon
entry.content: Species information: Small to large long-lived tree 6 - 30 m high. Phyllodes narrowly elliptic, lanceolate or oblanceolate, 4â16 cm long, 6â25 mm wide, main veins 3â5, raised, distant. Flower heads, cream to yellow in clusters of 2 to 5. Seed black, encircled by pink fleshy tissue. One of the most wide-ranging trees in eastern Australia. Flowers Aug - Oct

entry.title: Acacia leprosa var. uninervia
entry.content: Species information: Bushy or openly branched shrubs 2â5 m tall. Phyllodes mostly (40â)70â140 mm long, (6â)8â15(â18) mm wide; with 1 longitudinal nerve, the nerve prominent; lateral nerves few to numerous, often quite evident (at least when dry) and distally coalescing to form a fine, continuous but uneven intra-marginal nerve on one or both sides of the phyllode. Flowers from late August to early October.

entry.title: Acacia gunnii
entry.content: Species information: Spreading, erect or prostrate shrub to 1 m high. Phyllodes variable but more or less asymmetrically triangular, with a spine. Spherical creamy pale yellow flower heads on long peduncles, one per leaf axil. Flowers Jun - Oct

entry.title: Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata
entry.content: Species information: Tree to 30 m high or spindly shrub. Leaves grey bluish-green, bipinnate with a raised gland at the junction of each pinna pair. Spherical flower heads, bright yellow in clusters of 25 - 35 . Flowers Jul - Oct
